Reviewing the Data

I notice a primary key, a few different types of acid, as well as the values pH, alcohol, and density. These last three are variables that might be affected by others like the acids, and the acids might be correlated with one another somehow. There are other variables, like total sulfur dioxides and free sulfur dioxides. Could they be related to one another? Sugars, sulfates, quality and chlorides are also mentioned.

Looking into Some Particular Variables

Lets start by looking at the fixed acidity of the different red wines, just to get a feel for some of the data, and then move on to some other variables.

Fixed acidity vs citric acid, and fixed acidity vs density look interesting! Lets check those out in greater detail.

Fixed Acidity vs Citric Acid in Red Wines

The data definitely looks correlated, in fact the correlation is around .6717, one of the highest in the data set. It would make sense that the amount of citric acid correlates with the amount of fixed acidity in a wine, as citric acid is a type of acid.

Fixed Acidity vs Density in Red Wines

It looks as if there is a positive correlation between fixed acidity and density. Does this mean that the more acidic something is, the denser it is? Well, we do know that the correlation is around .6680.

Further exploration online found this study, and the data seems to show that the more acidic something is, the denser it is, although maybe this just goes for liquids soluable in water.

https://wissen.science-and-fun.de/chemistry/chemistry/density-tables/density-of-sulfuric-acid-and-sulfur-trioxide/

pH and Density

## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

There does seem to be a small correlation here! It looks like density and pH are slightly correlated, with the correlation coefficient being around -.6830. That means the lower the pH, the higher the density, on average. We might notice that this is nearly the opposite of the relationship between fixed acidity and density, and this is because acidic substances by definition have a lower pH.
